We will have band camp next week for all band students grades 7-12. Details below:

--9:30a-11:30a, Monday through Thursday
--Enter through the theater doors no earlier than 9:15a
--Bring your instrument
--Health/temp screenings will be done daily
--Bring a water bottle, mask, and sun screen
--Wear closed-toe shoes
--As much time will be spent outside as possible
--Attendance is not mandatory, but the more the better!
--Social distancing will be practiced both inside and outside

Even with so many changes, we're looking forward to an exciting year!

WE ARE EXCITED!!! The Girls Multi-Sport Camp begins Monday the 27th and ends on Thursday the 30th. The camp is from 9:00-12:00. A couple of things‚Ä¶.
1. Enter through the main doors at the high school
2. Temperatures will be taken each day, any camper with a temp over 100.4 will not be allowed to participate
3. COVID waivers will be collected (you may print one from the Little Eagle FB page) or complete one on Monday morning. 6th graders if you have already completed a waiver you do not need to do another one.
4. Campers need to bring a water bottle with their name clearly marked. No drinking fountains will be available for use.
5. If you ordered a t-shirt please bring $15 cash or a check made out to Wood River Volleyball on Monday.
#togetherwerebetter
#workingforbanners

post_text: This years summer reading program at Maltman Memorial Library will be a little different, it will be on line with Reader Zone. On May 1st, but not before, you can log on and record your reading minutes. This program is for pre-K through those finishing 12th grade. This program runs May 1st through July 31st. Your reading program is Maltman Memorial and the code is 9b346, click on the group you are in. More information to come on the Library's facebook page. If using a phone, download the app. We are doing reading minutes for all groups. On Aug. 3rd, at the end of the programs, we will be drawing one name from each of the six groups for one book as the grand prizes in each group. At this time we are working on other reading incentives for all readers. Happy Reading! Our Summer craft program is being revamped and more information in the following weeks as to crafts in a bag. Check out the Maltman Memorial Library facebook page for more information!

post_text:
In order to help make lunch deliveries go smoothly for our volunteers, we have a few requests for families. We appreciate your help with these items!
1. Please call either school (583-2525 OR 583-2249), if you will not be home to accept a lunch delivery. Due to food handling guidelines, we are unable to leave unattended lunches on doorsteps.
2. Please leave a tote or box outside your door, so that deliveries can be made without person-to-person contact.
3. For everyone‚Äôs safety, please keep pets in a secure location while lunches are being delivered.
4. Delivery routes are pretty well established, so lunches should come at roughly the same time each day. It would be appreciated if someone could meet volunteers at the door promptly. This will allow the drivers to stay on schedule for other deliveries.

post_text: Since our last announcement, food pantry use in Wood River has continued to increase. Because of your donations (both food and financial), we have been able to sustain operation even with these increased needs. We anticipate that this is ‚Äúnew normal‚Äù for our pantry, and we ask for your continued support as we keep our shelves stocked. In particular, canned tuna/chicken and boxed mac and cheeses are our most pressing need. Other items we can use are canned soups, fruits and veggies, jelly in squeeze bottles, peanut butter, cereal and granola bars. Financial donations are accepted as well. If you have food or financial donations, they can be given to Nancy Devore, or any of the pastors. Financial donations may be mailed to PO Box 333, Wood River. Thank you for your generosity!

post_text:
Mark your calendars for the Drug Take Back on April 25th.
The DEA‚Äôs Take Back Day events provide an opportunity for Americans to prevent drug addiction and overdose deaths.

What is accepted:
ANY PILL FORM MEDICATION including prescription and over the counter

What we cannot accept:
Liquids, Needles, Pressurized containers (inhalers)

This is entirely anonymous; the medications are brought in and dropped in a box and you are free to walk away. We do not collect any information- the pills are disposed of in an incinerator, so no need to identify if you do not wish to take that time.

post_text: We have been preparing for state cheer for what seems like forever. We went to Nebraska Cheer Center in Lincoln this summer to help us with a routine for the competition. We decided to enter into the Tumbling division because we have some awesome senior leaders to help with our tumbling skills. Our captains Marlie Ruge and Alyana Newell helped our girls all year to get to the level of tumbling we had for state. The cheerleaders participated at the state cheer competition on Saturday February 22. We were able to bring home 2nd place in our division. We are so proud of the hard work and dedication of our ladies to our goal of participating in state this year. You ladies were amazing!

The cheerleaders participated at the state cheer competition on Saturday February 22. We were able to bring home 2nd place in our division.
